Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T4]: Measuring User Awareness with Phishing Simulators

 

A security awareness program would not be effective without a method to measure improvements over time. After educating users about email threats, it's time to put what they have learned into action and see how they will respond. Answers to questions such as how many users will fall for a possible attack over time provide a statistical way to measure improvements.

 

It's highly recommended to determine the security awareness level of end-users before and after starting a training program. That will help us figure out how good is the conducted training, spot before and after improvements, and determine limitations with the training program.

 

Phishing simulators allow SOC analysts to test their end-users for phishing before the bad guys do. Analysts use it to simulate phishing attacks and create and manage phishing campaigns exactly as the attackers do. There are many phishing simulators, commercial and opensource, but we will discuss a single opensource tool called GoPhish.

 

I have used GoPhish in many email security assessment engagements and found it a reliable and efficient solution. One of the best things that GoPhish offers is privacy. SOC analysts can deploy it on-premises without the need to share your users' data with a third party. Most if not all commercial solutions require you to provide them with a list of users' emails so they can send phishing emails from their mail servers. As a SOC analyst, the last thing you need is to experience is seeing all users' emails -also known as GAL- leaked online because of a third-party breach!

 

Another good thing about GoPhish is the ease of deployment. Jordan Wright -the tool author- wrote an excellent blog about how he wanted users to get GoPhish up and running in minimal time. He even automated creating demo data so users could focus on exploring the tool instead of configuring it. If you decide to host an on-premises instance of GoPhish, you can use the prebuilt installers to deploy it on a corporate server. 

 

To get GoPhish up and running, here are the things we need to configure:

 

  1. Sending Profile: the mail server that will send the phishing emails. In a typical production deployment, this should be your internal mail server.
  2. Landing Page: the HTML page users will see when they click the phishing links they receive.
  3. Email Templates: the content of the phishing emails sent to users.
  4. Users & Groups: list of users -email recipients- who will receive the phishing mail.
  5. Campaigns: a campaign is a way to group specific attack details. A campaign consists of a sending profile, landing page, email template, and user group. For example, you can create one campaign to phish your IT department and another to phish your c-level users (i.e., CEO, CFO, CTOetc.). Each campaign will have a different email template, landing page, and target users.

 

Here is what a typical running campaign will look like:

As we can see, the email was sent to 299 recipients. 155 opened the mail, 22 clicked, and one user only submitted credentials. We can also see the submitted credentials.

 

In a previous engagement, I saw many submitted credentials and thought users awareness was miserable. It turned out that most of them submitted fake credentials like go/away to let the sender know they were aware it was a phishing attempt. They had their awareness training a couple of weeks before the engagement :). That may be ok sometimes, but its not recommended to click any link in suspicious mailone never knows what a hyperlink would do!
 

Another thing to consider is that GoPhish uses a self-signed SSL certificate to host the landing page, and the browser will display a certificate warning when users visit the page. In a typical production deployment, you do not want something like this to happen. If you host the phishing page internally, you can utilize your PKI solution to mark the certificate as trusted in your corporate network. If the phishing page will be hosted on the internet, use a free service like LetsEncrypt to obtain a valid certificate.

 

Important note:

Before conducting a simulated phishing campaign, it is essential to be mindful of the laws and regulations in your country and the organization's policies and approvals. You must ensure that it is well-planned and approved by relevant stakeholders to avoid any potential issues that may arise when users submit their credentials.

Communicate effectively with the management regarding the timing and scope of the campaign to avoid any misunderstandings that could lead to negative consequences such as termination of employment or legal intervention.
